1
00:00:08,885 --> 00:00:11,387
Bailey:

2
00:00:11,388 --> 00:00:12,555
Bailey?

3
00:00:12,556 --> 00:00:13,556
Bailey, you okay?

4
00:00:15,267 --> 00:00:17,059
Bailey. Give me your belt.

5
00:00:17,060 --> 00:00:18,686
Your belt. Give me your belt.

6
00:00:18,687 --> 00:00:20,229
Control, this is
Detective Lopez.

7
00:00:20,230 --> 00:00:21,814
I have a fully engulfed
structure fire

8
00:00:21,815 --> 00:00:24,275
at 1600 Quiet Valley Lane
in Newhall.

9
00:00:24,276 --> 00:00:26,068
I need fire rescue and an RA

10
00:00:26,069 --> 00:00:28,070
for a woman with a puncture
wound to her left leg.

11
00:00:28,071 --> 00:00:29,196
Fred's still in there.

12
00:00:29,197 --> 00:00:30,240
Don't move.

13
00:00:33,493 --> 00:00:35,035
We have to help him! Bailey.

14
00:00:35,036 --> 00:00:37,037
No one could have survived that.

15
00:00:37,038 --> 00:00:39,749
Bailey, he's gone.

16
00:00:52,095 --> 00:00:53,804
Hey, whoa, whoa!
What are you doing?

17
00:00:53,805 --> 00:00:55,014
I'm fine.

18
00:00:55,015 --> 00:00:56,015
You're not fine. Come on.

19
00:00:56,016 --> 00:00:57,933
Back in bed. Back in bed.

20
00:00:57,934 --> 00:00:58,934
Watch your legs.

21
00:00:59,811 --> 00:01:00,729
How's the patient?

22
00:01:00,730 --> 00:01:02,021
Did they find Fred?

23
00:01:02,022 --> 00:01:03,564
I'm afraid so.

24
00:01:03,565 --> 00:01:07,443
His body sustained extensive
damage in the explosion,

25
00:01:07,444 --> 00:01:10,070
but the Deputy Fire Chief
made a positive ID.

26
00:01:10,071 --> 00:01:11,447
I'm sorry.
I know you were close.

27
00:01:11,448 --> 00:01:12,615
I thought we were.

28
00:01:12,616 --> 00:01:14,158
Then he turned out to be
a serial killer,

29
00:01:14,159 --> 00:01:16,702
so it would seem that
the guy I liked

30
00:01:16,703 --> 00:01:19,163
was just a disguise
he was wearing.

31
00:01:19,164 --> 00:01:20,873
Lopez: Seems like he knew
we were onto him ‐‐

32
00:01:20,874 --> 00:01:22,124
wanted to go out
on his own terms ‐‐

33
00:01:22,125 --> 00:01:23,626
one last fire.

34
00:01:23,627 --> 00:01:26,170
Hey, you okay?
I heard you got the guy.

35
00:01:26,171 --> 00:01:27,755
Thanks to Nolan and Bailey.

36
00:01:27,756 --> 00:01:29,131
So we need to close out
the case tomorrow.

37
00:01:29,132 --> 00:01:30,549
Do you mind
partnering with Lopez?

38
00:01:30,550 --> 00:01:31,759
Yeah, whatever you need.

39
00:01:31,760 --> 00:01:33,427
Sarge, I was hoping
I could take the day tomorrow,

40
00:01:33,428 --> 00:01:35,179
just to help Bailey
get settled at my place.

41
00:01:35,180 --> 00:01:36,805
I told you I'd be fine
in my apartment.

42
00:01:36,806 --> 00:01:38,557
I'm sure you would be,
but I'm not budging on this.

43
00:01:38,558 --> 00:01:39,892
I don't want to impose.

44
00:01:39,893 --> 00:01:41,895
It's not an imposition.

45
00:01:46,191 --> 00:01:49,568
Okay, here we go.

46
00:01:49,569 --> 00:01:51,236
Watch your step.

47
00:01:51,237 --> 00:01:52,780
You're pretty good on those.

48
00:01:52,781 --> 00:01:54,865
Gymnast all through
high school and college.

49
00:01:54,866 --> 00:01:58,452
If you can sprain it, twist it,
or dislocate it, I have.

50
00:01:58,453 --> 00:02:00,329
All I want is a couch.

51
00:02:00,330 --> 00:02:01,580
You don't want to go
straight to bed?

52
00:02:01,581 --> 00:02:02,915
Not yet.

53
00:02:02,916 --> 00:02:06,210
First, I'm gonna have
a big cry and eat some carbs,

54
00:02:06,211 --> 00:02:07,961
probably cry again,

55
00:02:07,962 --> 00:02:08,962
then I can sleep.

56
00:02:08,963 --> 00:02:10,047
Okay.

57
00:02:10,048 --> 00:02:11,591
I will get the tissues
and ice cream.

58
00:02:14,344 --> 00:02:15,428
Thank you.

59
00:02:17,681 --> 00:02:18,932
You're welcome.

60
00:02:23,186 --> 00:02:25,229
So I rolled a stop sign.
What's the big deal?

61
00:02:25,230 --> 00:02:27,022
No, you ran a red light
and a stop sign,

62
00:02:27,023 --> 00:02:28,399
and when we tried to
pull you over,

63
00:02:28,400 --> 00:02:30,442
you flipped us off and led us on
a medium‐speed pursuit.

64
00:02:30,443 --> 00:02:33,404
I was late for an appointment
with Orchid, my life coach.

65
00:02:33,405 --> 00:02:34,863
Well, she's doing
a terrible job.

66
00:02:34,864 --> 00:02:36,407
Go stand over there.

67
00:02:36,408 --> 00:02:38,785
Is there anything we can do
about this lighting?

68
00:02:39,869 --> 00:02:42,079
Hey, so I've been
meaning to talk to you

69
00:02:42,080 --> 00:02:44,164
about our bet
from the treasure hunt.

70
00:02:44,165 --> 00:02:46,458
The bet I won?
No, the bet I won.

71
00:02:46,459 --> 00:02:47,960
I had the gold in my hands.

72
00:02:47,961 --> 00:02:50,421
Because I stopped to arrest
an armed gunman.

73
00:02:50,422 --> 00:02:52,047
Eh, technically, I arrested him.

74
00:02:52,048 --> 00:02:54,550
All you did was stand there
with your arm out.

75
00:02:54,551 --> 00:02:55,844
Which is even more impressive.

76
00:02:57,011 --> 00:02:58,178
Sir, what do you think?

77
00:02:58,179 --> 00:02:59,097
What?

78
00:02:59,098 --> 00:03:00,180
You okay, sir?

79
00:03:00,181 --> 00:03:01,181
Something wrong
with the booking slip?

80
00:03:01,182 --> 00:03:02,391
No. No. What do you need?

81
00:03:02,392 --> 00:03:03,559
An umpire.

82
00:03:03,560 --> 00:03:06,019
Um, who do you think won
our treasure hunt bet?

83
00:03:06,020 --> 00:03:07,980
It was a tie. Oh...

84
00:03:07,981 --> 00:03:10,149
We need a rematch.
Oh, I have an idea.

85
00:03:10,150 --> 00:03:11,942
Why don't we race each other
in an escape room?

86
00:03:11,943 --> 00:03:12,943
Hard pass.

87
00:03:12,944 --> 00:03:14,069
No, we need a neutral party

88
00:03:14,070 --> 00:03:15,590
to decide the terms
of the competition.

89
00:03:18,158 --> 00:03:20,242
And that would be me. Okay.

90
00:03:20,243 --> 00:03:23,162
I'm gonna assign each of you
a penal code violation

91
00:03:23,163 --> 00:03:24,788
at random.

92
00:03:24,789 --> 00:03:26,790
First one to make
their arrest wins.

93
00:03:26,791 --> 00:03:31,211
Officer Chen,
your crime is 266i ‐‐

94
00:03:31,212 --> 00:03:33,046
encourage, influence,
or persuade someone

95
00:03:33,047 --> 00:03:34,715
to become a prostitute.

96
00:03:34,716 --> 00:03:38,552
Sergeant Bradford,
yours is 148.4.

97
00:03:38,553 --> 00:03:39,845
Oh, come on.

98
00:03:39,846 --> 00:03:41,722
Willfully and maliciously
tampers with or breaks

99
00:03:41,723 --> 00:03:42,890
fire protection equipment?

100
00:03:42,891 --> 00:03:44,475
You knew that
off the top of your head?

101
00:03:44,476 --> 00:03:46,101
You didn't?

102
00:03:46,102 --> 00:03:47,644
Hmm. It's unfair.

103
00:03:47,645 --> 00:03:49,272
So is life. Deal with it.

104
00:03:50,148 --> 00:03:51,399
Hmm.

105
00:03:52,942 --> 00:03:54,444
Oh, thank you.

106
00:03:59,240 --> 00:04:01,200
Is there any way
I can get a single?

107
00:04:01,201 --> 00:04:02,618
No. I'm afraid not.

108
00:04:02,619 --> 00:04:03,744
Maybe I can make a donation

109
00:04:03,745 --> 00:04:05,162
to the policemen's fund
or something.

110
00:04:05,163 --> 00:04:06,705
Okay, don't add bribery
to your charge.

111
00:04:06,706 --> 00:04:07,915
It's a whole other
stack of paperwork.

112
00:04:07,916 --> 00:04:09,124
Let's go.

113
00:04:09,125 --> 00:04:11,084
What if I give you
someone worse?

114
00:04:11,085 --> 00:04:13,378
I know about a real crime.

115
00:04:13,379 --> 00:04:15,172
I could cut a deal, right?

116
00:04:15,173 --> 00:04:16,298
Like in the movies.

117
00:04:16,299 --> 00:04:19,009
That depends. What's the crime?

118
00:04:19,010 --> 00:04:21,678
They're alleging you beat a man
to death with a tire iron.

119
00:04:21,679 --> 00:04:23,972
Dude deserved it.
He's banging my ex‐wife.

120
00:04:23,973 --> 00:04:25,933
That's a street violation.
That demands repercussions.

121
00:04:25,934 --> 00:04:29,228
Right. Sadly, street violations
don't hold up in court.

122
00:04:29,229 --> 00:04:30,771
Says here there's a witness.

123
00:04:30,772 --> 00:04:32,815
Yeah, some nosy old man
across the street

124
00:04:32,816 --> 00:04:34,274
saw the whole thing.

125
00:04:34,275 --> 00:04:35,984
Well, that's a problem. Why?

126
00:04:35,985 --> 00:04:37,486
He's the one that's watching us
like some perv.

127
00:04:37,487 --> 00:04:39,530
Be that as it may, we should
start talking plea deal.

128
00:04:39,531 --> 00:04:40,823
A ‐‐ No!

129
00:04:40,824 --> 00:04:42,199
No way, man, okay?

130
00:04:42,200 --> 00:04:44,159
Elijah said you could fix this.

131
00:04:44,160 --> 00:04:46,412
Elijah makes too many promises.

132
00:04:47,705 --> 00:04:49,248
But I'll do what I can.

133
00:04:49,249 --> 00:04:51,583
In the meantime, hey,
you know the drill ‐‐

134
00:04:51,584 --> 00:04:52,835
best behavior.

135
00:04:52,836 --> 00:04:54,295
Don't talk to anyone.

136
00:04:55,797 --> 00:04:57,465
I noticed you got a new client.

137
00:04:58,466 --> 00:04:59,591
Yeah.

138
00:04:59,592 --> 00:05:00,676
Business is good.

139
00:05:00,677 --> 00:05:02,010
Lately, it seems like
all your clients

140
00:05:02,011 --> 00:05:03,805
are on Elijah Stone's payroll.

141
00:05:05,557 --> 00:05:08,767
Well, every criminal defendant
is entitled to a defense,

142
00:05:08,768 --> 00:05:11,353
regardless of who
they associate with.

143
00:05:11,354 --> 00:05:14,022
Yes, and up 'til recently,

144
00:05:14,023 --> 00:05:16,942
you've always chosen
to represent the underdog.

145
00:05:16,943 --> 00:05:18,861
But now, the way
things are going,

146
00:05:18,862 --> 00:05:20,696
you're on your way
to becoming a mob lawyer.

147
00:05:20,697 --> 00:05:22,865
I think that's a bit extreme.

148
00:05:22,866 --> 00:05:26,034
And there's only two ways
I've ever seen that turn out ‐‐

149
00:05:26,035 --> 00:05:29,037
you end up disbarred
and indicted

150
00:05:29,038 --> 00:05:30,622
or you end up dead.

151
00:05:30,623 --> 00:05:31,833
Okay, I think that ‐‐

152
00:05:34,752 --> 00:05:36,795
You know how much I care
for Angela.

153
00:05:36,796 --> 00:05:39,464
If you ever get in
over your head,

154
00:05:39,465 --> 00:05:40,842
you can come see me.

155
00:05:43,344 --> 00:05:45,762
I appreciate that.

156
00:05:45,763 --> 00:05:47,180
But you know
I would never do anything

157
00:05:47,181 --> 00:05:49,641
to jeopardize my family.

158
00:05:49,642 --> 00:05:51,269
I hope not.

159
00:05:57,442 --> 00:05:59,818
I'll let you know if
there's gonna be a service.

160
00:05:59,819 --> 00:06:01,404
Okay, bye.

161
00:06:03,156 --> 00:06:04,489
I made breakfast.

162
00:06:04,490 --> 00:06:05,490
You sure did.

163
00:06:05,491 --> 00:06:07,409
I was feeling
a little powerless,

164
00:06:07,410 --> 00:06:08,911
so this happened.

165
00:06:08,912 --> 00:06:10,078
You're not gonna
hear me complaining.

166
00:06:10,079 --> 00:06:12,331
This smells amazing.

167
00:06:12,332 --> 00:06:13,373
Who was that on the phone?

168
00:06:13,374 --> 00:06:14,708
Fred's old captain.

169
00:06:14,709 --> 00:06:16,293
His family's dealing
with so much,

170
00:06:16,294 --> 00:06:19,046
so I'm contacting some
of his former colleagues.

171
00:06:19,047 --> 00:06:21,214
That's me.
I'll take this real quick.

172
00:06:21,215 --> 00:06:22,215
Hey, what's up?

173
00:06:22,216 --> 00:06:23,717
I just wanted to call
and check in

174
00:06:23,718 --> 00:06:25,093
and see how Bailey's doing.

175
00:06:25,094 --> 00:06:27,220
Uh, she's made four
different kinds of pancakes.

176
00:06:27,221 --> 00:06:28,680
I'm not sure
if that's good or bad.

177
00:06:28,681 --> 00:06:31,558
Yeah, the type A personality's
first stage of grief ‐‐ cooking.

178
00:06:31,559 --> 00:06:33,560
What's next? Uh, cleaning.

179
00:06:33,561 --> 00:06:35,228
Then organization.

180
00:06:35,229 --> 00:06:36,396
She can't fix what happened,

181
00:06:36,397 --> 00:06:37,940
but she can fix
every little thing

182
00:06:37,941 --> 00:06:39,274
that's wrong in her apartment.

183
00:06:39,275 --> 00:06:40,359
Uh, well, she's staying with me.

184
00:06:40,360 --> 00:06:42,569
Yeah, well,
when she changes the drapes,

185
00:06:42,570 --> 00:06:43,905
just roll with it. Right.

186
00:06:45,031 --> 00:06:47,116
Thanks for checking in.
I gotta go.

187
00:06:48,660 --> 00:06:50,911
I am so sorry, David,
but can you repeat that?

188
00:06:50,912 --> 00:06:53,080
When were you at Lake Mead
with Fred?

189
00:06:53,081 --> 00:06:54,289
David: Last Fourth of July.

190
00:06:54,290 --> 00:06:56,124
And you were with him
the whole time? Yep.

191
00:06:56,125 --> 00:06:58,335
It was supposed to be
a week‐long camping trip,

192
00:06:58,336 --> 00:07:01,630
but, uh, a couple days in,
he got a nasty stomach bug.

193
00:07:01,631 --> 00:07:04,424
He got so dehydrated,
I had to take him to Henderson.

194
00:07:04,425 --> 00:07:06,259
He spent the rest of the trip
in the hospital.

195
00:07:06,260 --> 00:07:08,553
Never thought that'd be
the last time I'd ever see him.

196
00:07:08,554 --> 00:07:09,763
And he will be missed.

197
00:07:09,764 --> 00:07:11,056
I will let you know
if there's any details

198
00:07:11,057 --> 00:07:12,057
about the funeral.

199
00:07:12,058 --> 00:07:13,517
Take care, okay? Thanks, Bailey.

200
00:07:13,518 --> 00:07:15,102
You too.

201
00:07:15,103 --> 00:07:17,312
Okay, I know
I'm on pain pills and all,

202
00:07:17,313 --> 00:07:18,939
but you heard
what I just heard, right?

203
00:07:18,940 --> 00:07:21,733
We know Fred was in Nevada
July 8th,

204
00:07:21,734 --> 00:07:25,195
and that lined up
with an unsolved arson‐homicide.

205
00:07:25,196 --> 00:07:26,780
But he was in the hospital.

206
00:07:26,781 --> 00:07:28,156
Fred has an alibi.

207
00:07:28,157 --> 00:07:29,866
That means Fred was set up,

208
00:07:29,867 --> 00:07:31,952
and the real killer
is still out there somewhere.

209
00:07:31,953 --> 00:07:33,161
What about the watch

210
00:07:33,162 --> 00:07:34,871
and all the keepsakes
I found in his house?

211
00:07:34,872 --> 00:07:37,999
Whoever framed Fred
must have planted them there,

212
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:39,042
counting on us finding them.

213
00:07:39,043 --> 00:07:40,085
I gotta call Lopez,

214
00:07:40,086 --> 00:07:41,878
have her reopen
the investigation.

215
00:07:41,879 --> 00:07:42,879
Don't just call.

216
00:07:42,880 --> 00:07:44,423
You need to go into work.

217
00:07:44,424 --> 00:07:45,299
Find that bastard.

218
00:07:45,300 --> 00:07:46,508
Are you sure?

219
00:07:46,509 --> 00:07:48,135
We have a deal, remember?

220
00:07:48,136 --> 00:07:49,469
I run toward fires.

221
00:07:49,470 --> 00:07:50,762
You run toward bullets.

222
00:07:50,763 --> 00:07:52,473
Time to run toward bullets.

223
00:07:53,766 --> 00:07:56,309
But not literally.

224
00:07:56,310 --> 00:07:57,687
Right.

225
00:08:03,651 --> 00:08:05,444
So, I have a list of locations
we should check out

226
00:08:05,445 --> 00:08:06,653
when we get back out on patrol.

227
00:08:06,654 --> 00:08:08,864
You know, just some places
that I think need

228
00:08:08,865 --> 00:08:10,115
a police presence.

229
00:08:10,116 --> 00:08:12,367
Places you're sure to get
your pandering collar?

230
00:08:12,368 --> 00:08:14,995
Oh. Yeah. Maybe.

231
00:08:14,996 --> 00:08:16,913
Is that really your focus?

232
00:08:16,914 --> 00:08:19,374
Our bet? Come on.

233
00:08:19,375 --> 00:08:20,709
I know that you bribed Nell

234
00:08:20,710 --> 00:08:24,004
to throw any "fire alarm
tampering" cases your way.

235
00:08:24,005 --> 00:08:25,839
Nell and I are friends. Mm.

236
00:08:25,840 --> 00:08:27,425
Sometimes, I give her
Dodgers tickets.

237
00:08:31,095 --> 00:08:32,763
Oh, finally.

238
00:08:32,764 --> 00:08:33,973
What's this all about?

239
00:08:35,183 --> 00:08:36,808
Mrs. Carter, I understand
that you've recently started

240
00:08:36,809 --> 00:08:38,101
your own skincare line.

241
00:08:38,102 --> 00:08:39,269
Yes.

242
00:08:39,270 --> 00:08:42,272
We're a small operation,
but we're growing.

243
00:08:42,273 --> 00:08:44,107
I'm hoping to get
a write‐up in Goop.

244
00:08:44,108 --> 00:08:45,984
I‐I don't know what that is.

245
00:08:45,985 --> 00:08:47,069
I'll explain later.

246
00:08:47,070 --> 00:08:48,111
Uh, a friend of yours

247
00:08:48,112 --> 00:08:49,863
gave us a jar
of your night cream.

248
00:08:49,864 --> 00:08:51,323
She claims that
one of the ingredients

249
00:08:51,324 --> 00:08:53,075
is tiger's blood ‐‐
like, literally,

250
00:08:53,076 --> 00:08:54,910
blood from an endangered animal.

251
00:08:54,911 --> 00:08:56,745
Firms the skin right up.

252
00:08:56,746 --> 00:08:59,581
Participating in
the endangered animal trade

253
00:08:59,582 --> 00:09:01,583
could land you in jail
for up to five years.

254
00:09:01,584 --> 00:09:03,835
You don't understand
the wellness game.

255
00:09:03,836 --> 00:09:05,128
It's cutthroat.

256
00:09:05,129 --> 00:09:06,838
I need to stand out.

257
00:09:06,839 --> 00:09:08,131
How else am I gonna compete

258
00:09:08,132 --> 00:09:10,008
with Sloan
and her vitamin business?

259
00:09:10,009 --> 00:09:13,678
I mean, everybody knows that
her B‐12 rejuvenation pills

260
00:09:13,679 --> 00:09:16,933
are just benzos
in fancy bottles.

261
00:09:18,559 --> 00:09:21,353
Um, she's selling
psychiatric drugs?

